communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Because fewer then 20% of children under 10 years of age have received at least one dose of measles vaccine, the outbreak is severe, especially with malnutrition probably playing a role exacerbating the disease. Higher mortality has been associated with secondary infections which apparently complicate the primary illness in malnourished children with measles. This is especially true if the children are also vitamin A deficient. Measles, especially with complications such as diarrhea, often results in failure to thrive. Measles may lead to kwashiorkor or marasmus in children who are underweight at the time that they get measles. Therefore, measles may result in, or aggravate, malnutrition, with a poor outcome for the child. - Mod.LK

